<div id="review_4256742076" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4256742076" />
    <a title="Antoinette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5328952-antoinette"><img alt="Antoinette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1503842818p2/5328952.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4256742076?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Antoinette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Antoinette" href="/user/show/5328952-antoinette">Antoinette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5328952-antoinette?shelf=bookclub">bookclub</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5328952-antoinette?shelf=american-literature">american-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5328952-antoinette?shelf=a-century-of-books-challenge">a-century-of-books-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5328952-antoinette?shelf=immigrant-experience">immigrant-experience</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5328952-antoinette?shelf=african-american">african-american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4256742076" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8964159220058679646">America, the land of promise, the land where dreams can come true. You just have to work hard, and you can make it! If only it was so easy.....<br/>In this book, we learn how difficult it is to achieve the American dream. So much depends on getting a green card: so much depends on getting a good job; so much depends on who you know.<br/><br/>We follow Jende and Neni as they both pursue their dreams: Jendi to provide for his family and Neni to go to school and become a pharmacist.<br/><br/>Jende becomes a chauffeur for C</span>
  <span id="freeText8964159220058679646" style="display:none">America, the land of promise, the land where dreams can come true. You just have to work hard, and you can make it! If only it was so easy.....<br />In this book, we learn how difficult it is to achieve the American dream. So much depends on getting a green card: so much depends on getting a good job; so much depends on who you know.<br /><br />We follow Jende and Neni as they both pursue their dreams: Jendi to provide for his family and Neni to go to school and become a pharmacist.<br /><br />Jende becomes a chauffeur for Clark and Cindy Edwards (through a connection), affluent people who have their own problems.<br />For all 4, things come to a head with the stock market crash of 2008.<br /><br />What I found most interesting was how no matter where you come from, you always bring your own culture with you- whether it be the food or your expectations and behaviour. Women were expected to be subservient to their husbands in Cameroon. Even though in NYC, Jende still expects that of Neni.<br />The other thing that struck me is how the people you leave behind assume you have money to help with everything that comes up back home. There was always a demand for them to send money home, which they lovingly did.<br /><br />Initially, I totally empathized with both Jende and Neni, but a couple of their behaviours disturbed me and I admit to losing some of my respect for them.<br /><br />The Edwards were put in it seemed to me to show the total extreme opposite of Jende and Neni- A power couple who had issues of their own.<br /><br />Overall, I really enjoyed the book. Made me reflect on my own parents and how difficult it must have been for them to emigrate to a country ( Canada ), where neither spoke English, but both seeking a better life for themselves and for their future children.<br /><br />Rich or poor in this book, one thing they all had in common was wanting what was best for their children. In the end, it really is all about family!!<br /><br />Published: 2016</span>
  <a data-text-id="8964159220058679646" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


